name: A Street Pump Station, 67 A Street
notes: Site Plan Review Approval and Public Way Access Permit. The project is  zoned Single Family Residental District (R-1).  Said parcel is shown on the Framingham Assessor's Sheet 276, Block 151, Lot 9.   The project is the construction of a wastewater Management Facility, approximately 9,600 square feet in size, with landscaping, parking, lighting, and drainage improvements on a parcel of land at 67 A Street.The East Framingham Sewer Improvement Project (EFSIP) includes the construction of a new gravity sewer on Concord Street from Old Connecticut Path to Arthur Street and within the former railroad right-of-way from Speen Street to School Street.  It also includes the construction of a new force main sewer from A Street to Old Connecticut Path.  This project will eliminate three sewer pump stations and several miles of force main, one of the largest contributors of sulfides in the Town'ss sewer system.  In addition, this project will eliminate several sanitary sewer overflows which constitute Clean Water Act violations and pose a threat to human health and the environment.In addition to the utility work, this project will develop the former railroad right-of-way into a recreational pathway that will also allow for operational access to the sewer pipe.  This work includes the construction of a new multi-use trail beginning at the northern terminus located at School Street, continuing along the abandoned railroad corridor before terminating at Cochituate Road (Route 30), a distance of approximately 1.5 miles.  The work includes a new hot mix bituminous asphalt trail, trail pull-offs, construction of two new pre-engineered bridges, an at-grade crossing of Old Connecticut Path, a crossing of the TJX entrance and a crossing of the Luchetti driveway.Completion of the EFSIP improvements is required under the terms of the Administrative Consent Order (ACO) with the Massachusetts Department of Environmental Protection (MADEP).  The sewer work proposed under this project has been preliminarily approved for low interest loans under the MADEP State Revolving Fund (SRF).  The project is also eligible for American Recovery and Reinvestment Act (ARRA) stimulus funding provided that the construction contracts are in place prior to February 17, 2010.The facility was sited based on a thorough alternatives analysis.  In addition to significantly reducing the amount of wastewater that crosses the Sudbury River, sitting the facility on the south side of the river eliminates the need for a siphon which would be problematic to maintain.  The ability to eliminate the Speen Street pump station could also only be accomplished if the proposed WWMF is located within a very narrow geographical area that meets the topographical constraints to allow gravity flow from the existing Speen Street station to Saxonville.  In addition to meeting the topographical constraints, the proposed location does not require the acquisition of any non-town owned property.  Locating the facility closer to the High School parking lot was considered, but the construction and operability issues associated with making the wetwell even deeper make that infeasible.

name: La Cantina Restaurant, 911 Waverly Street
notes: Site Plan Review Approval and Special Permit for Use and Special Permit for Proximity of Parking Spaces to Principal Use. The project is zoned Restaurant use at the property located at 911 and 921 Waverly Street, zoned General Manufacturing (M) and to provide parking at 904 and 920 Waverly Street zoned Business (B).  The premises are shown on Framingham Assessors Plan Sheet 149, Block 306, Lots 3 and 4 and Sheet 124, Block 253, Lots 2 and 15.  the Plan includes the construction of an addition to the Restaurant facility.  The addition consists of approximately 3,494 square feet. In addition to the expansion, additional space is being added as a result of the expansion of the second floor.   The second floor was expanded approximately 8 feet along the front of the building.  The total area of the addition and the second floor (346 square feet) results in a total increase of 3,840 square feet.  The second floor is being converted to a function area with 90 seats accessed by the elevator being installed in the addition.As a result of the changes to the Restaurant Lot, the building area increased from 10,644 square feet to 14,448 square feet, thereby establishing a Floor Area Ratio of .7,(existing F.A.R. of .52), as authorized by the Zoning Board of Appeals.  The changes will also result in an increase in the seating for the Restaurant patrons of 43 and an increase in the function seating for 4 patrons.Changes to the property located at 904 and 920 Waverly Street (Parking Lot) are also proposed.  The design for the parking area of the Parking Lot is in full compliance of the By-Law.  The changes to the Parking Lot also include the demolition of the existing automobile repair facility.   With the changes, the Open Space Area on the Parking Lot increases from .04 to .27.    Changes to the Parking Lot include the installation of a new drainage system, significant landscaping and the elimination of one driveway on Waverly Street.The totality of the changes to the site result in the Project being in compliance after the issuance of the Zoning Board of Appeals√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢ Decisions, with the requirements of the By-Law, except for the location of the parking spaces for the Restaurant Facility across Waverly Street and the need for a Special Permit for the increase in Restaurant Operations.  As depicted on the Site Plan, 122 parking spaces are provided for the Restaurant Operations, as modified, and the existing Barber Shop, as required under the By-Law.  The Plans also include the upgrading of the building facade.  Safety is also improved through the elimination of one of the driveways along Waverly Street.  In discussions of the Board, concerns were noted for the crossing of Waverly Street.  It was noted there is an existing street light in the area of the driveway and crossing area.  As a result of comments from the Planning Board, the Plan was revised to include Bollard lighting and signage to direct customers along the sidewalk to the crosswalk at the Winter Street intersection.  It was also noted that the Massachusetts Highway Department is in the process of making improvements to the Winter Street intersection and plans to move the crosswalk closer to the Restaurant Operations.

name: McDonalds, 343 Cochituate Road
notes: Site Plan Review Approval.Zoned Business District(B) and Regional Center Overlay District (RC).  Said parcel is shown on the Framingham Assessor's Sheet 244, Block 108, Lots 18E & 18F. The contained a pre-existing nonconforming use with a 5100 square foot McDonalds Building.  The site is fully developed consisting of an outdated structure, 92 parking spaces, two driveways, several existing non-conformities, a general lack of landscaping, poor site circulation for vehicles, pedestrians and bicycles.New Project: The  new McDonalds Building  propose to build a new 5,250 square foot building that would conform with current zoning, improve site circulation by reconfiguring the parking field and reduce impervious surface coverage through new landscaping and reduced parking count to 64 spaces. The project includes a double drive-thru to mitigate queuing issues as well as improve site circulation. Signage will be brought into compliance with the new Sign By-law.  The project will utilize existing grading and drainage with a few modifications, the addition of building sprinklers, fire hydrant, 3 catch basins, stormceptor, settling basin, and a grease trap. The landscaping would be upgraded with the addition of 22 trees, 400 shrubs and over 300 perennials and depressed islands for recharge.

name: Charles River Medical Associates, 561-571 Union Street
notes: Amends a Site Plan Review and Special Permit for Use, Reduction in the Required Number of Parking Spaces, and Public Way Access Permit. The property is zoned Office and Professional (P), Assessor's Sheet 203, Block 4, Lots 1 and 2A. Renovation to an existing office building for medical use and reconstruct the existing parking lot, the existing drainage system, lighting and landscaping for the property.Charles River proposes to demolish the existing building at 561 Union Avenue, a wood frame structure containing a total gross floor area of approximately 4,000 square feet.  The existing building at 571 Union Avenue will be renovated, and a new entry way and elevator will be added as shown on the plans so that the building will be handicapped accessible.  The entire building will be converted to medical use.   The existing parking lot will be reconstructed.  The existing pavement will be reclaimed to the maximum extent feasible.  Work includes removing some paved area closest to the Sudbury River, constructing a new drainage system, including a detention area, constructing new curb cuts along Union Avenue, and increasing the amount of landscaped areas along the site boundaries and within the parking lot.   The gross floor area ratio of buildings on the site will be reduced from approximately 0.35 existing to 0.30 proposed.  The landscaped surface ratio will also be increased.  There are currently 89 off-street parking spaces on the site, although not all conform to current standards.  Proposed conditions provide for 103 conforming, off-street parking spaces, including the requisite number of handicapped and van accessible spaces.

name: The Wine Vault, 428 Franklin Street
notes: Site Plan Review Approval, Special Permit for Use and Special Permit for Reduction in the Required Number of Parking Spaces.Zoned Light Manufacturing District (M-1).The parcel is shown on the Framingham Assessor's  Map Sheet 283, Block 1, Lot 12. The project consists of the renovation and re-use of the building as warehouse/storage use.  The primary use will be for climate-controlled, wine storage areas.   Customers will be able to access the facility to load or remove wine from their storage vaults.  The facility will have an automated security gate and overhead doors to the building that the customer can open with a security code.  They will be able to drive into the building, access their space and then drive out.  The building will also be used for storage by another company owned by the Silvermans, and a portion may also be leased to a third party.   The building will also contain accessory offices, a lounge area and rest rooms. The interior and exterior of the building will be renovated, including the construction of additional mezzanine areas for storage. name: The Learning Center for the Deaf, 848 Central Street
notes: Site Plan Review, Public Way Access Permit, and Approval to ""Modify"" a Scenic Way. The property is zonedSingle Family Residental (R-3) and shown on Framingham Assessors Plan Sheet 227, Block 2, Lots 4A, 5, 6, 7 and 8 and Sheet 229, Blocks 92 and 93, Lots 14, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20, 21, 81 and 82.  Construction of a new building for the use as an early childhood development center, classrooms and a library, and off-street parking on the property located at 848 Central Street and Kellogg Street.The proposed project is the demolition of an existing building on Kellogg Street (the building is not numbered, but is adjacent to 62 Kellogg Street) and the construction of a new, larger building in the same location.  The existing building is a converted barn, and is no longer suitable to accommodate the needs of The Learning Center.  The building was constructed in 1878 of post and beam construction, and is no longer structurally sound.  The HVAC system is antiquated and not in compliance with applicable energy codes.  The building also is not in compliance with ADA regulations.  The Board was told that it was determined that it would not be feasible to attempt to renovate and expand the existing building. The existing building has a footprint of 4,593 square feet and a gross floor area of 9,186 square feet.  The proposed building will have a footprint of approximately 9,875 square feet and a gross floor area of approximately 19,750 square feet.  The building will be used by The Learning Center as an early childhood development center and will contain classrooms and related facilities, and will also contain a library.  The new building will be fully accessible and will comply with all applicable codes and regulations.The other component of the project is the construction of a new, off-street parking lot.  The parking lot will have a single entrance/exit on Kellogg Street, and will contain 35 parking spaces.  In order to minimize drainage impacts, a portion of the parking lot will be constructed with a new type of porous pavement known as Flexi-Pave.

name: District Court Redevelopment
notes: The proposed building at 65 Washington Street is a hybrid ‚Äúplatform‚Äù building using fire treated wood framing above a steel and concrete podium. The base of the building has been designed to be a contemporary interpretation of urban storefront design, with stone and steel column covers, fretwork, planter boxes, and awnings. The overall building is designed to adhere to the current historic patterns of Washington Street with a retail ground floor and residential above, using a combination of traditional brick and metal panels, with stone details.The first floor will contain 3000 sf of commercial space, as well as the lobby for the condominium and some enclosed garage space. The second floor of the building contains residential dwelling units and shared amenity space. The remaining floors are purely residential, and there are 61 dwelling units total, including 6 affordable units. The only basement area proposed is the existing lower level of the district court building which will be used for additional parking.

name: The Reserve
notes: Eastland  Partners,  Inc  (‚ÄúEastland‚Äù,  or  the ‚ÄúProponent‚Äù),  proposes  the  construction of a new multi-use  development  on  an assembly  of  parcels  along  Southbridge  Road  (Mass  Route 20)  in Oxford,  Massachusetts  and  off  Albert  Street  in Auburn,  Massachusetts  (the  ""Project  Site"").  Refer  to  Figure 1  for  the  Project  Site locus  map.   The Project  represents  an extraordinary  economic  development  opportunity  for  Auburn, Oxford,  and  the region.   The overall  development  consists of  160,000¬±  square feet  of  potential commercial  building  space  and  320  two-bedroom  condominiums  in  Oxford,  and  324  units  of affordable  rental  housing  apartments  and 8  two-bedroom  condominiums  in Auburn.   The full build-out  of  the  development  will be  phased  over  a  12-to  15-year  period.    Development  of  the Project  Site  provides  a  unique opportunity  to  create additional  affordable  housing,  spur commercial  development,  and  provide ample public  benefits,  such  as  320  units  of  life  stage housing,  and  new  public  open space.   The  project  has  undertaken a  variety  of  feasibility  studies  including  drinking water  and wastewater  analyses,  a  greenhouse  gas  analysis,  wetland  resource area  evaluations,  and several  traffic  impact  assessments.   All  feasible measures  have been taken  by  the Proponent  to avoid  impacts  on the environment  or,  to  the extent  impacts  cannot  be avoided,  to  minimize and/or  mitigate  the impacts  to  the maximum  extent  practicable.    Finally,  the Proponent  has  committed  to  several  community  benefits,  which  include,  providing construction  assistance  to  the Auburn Water  District  (AWD)  with  their  connection to  the Worcester  Water  System,  currently  being  reviewed  under  EEA  #16070,  an  allocation  of $500,000 as  a  ‚ÄúLocal  Impact  Offset  Expense‚Äù  to  the Town of  Auburn,  100¬±  acres  of  open space,   and  an overall  development  program  consistent  with the  goals  and  objectives  of  the  Master Plans  in  both communities,  Central  Mass  Regional  Planning  Commission,  and  the region.

name: Village at Grafton Woods
notes: The Project entails redevelopment of aportion of the former Grafton State Hospital within the limits of an approximately 8.8-acre ProjectSite (8 Pine Street, Parcel ID 5-0-5) that is owned by the Town of Grafton, located on the eastside of Pine Street, north of an existing Massachusetts Bay Transit Authority (MBTA) rail line. Theparcel is part of the larger former Grafton State Hospital Campus identified as 100 Pine Street.The subject parcel abuts the Town of Shrewsbury municipal boundary to the north.Development plans include the demolition of the existing site buildings and redevelopment ofresidential and commercial structures with associated parking areas and garages. The Projectalso includes on-site improvements to roadways, parking, and utility infrastructure.The Applicant won the right to develop the Project through a competitive solicitation issued by theTown of Grafton in December 2019. The 2019 Request for Proposals (RFP) sought proposals forredevelopment of the 8 Pine Street parcel. The Town of Grafton acquired the parcel throughentering into a Sales Partnership Agreement with the Massachusetts Division of Capital AssetManagement and Maintenance (DCAMM). A Land Disposition Agreement was executed in August2019 (Appendix E) for the 8 Pine Street parcel and GSX-ODG has entered into a Purchase andSale Agreement with the Town.The Project Site (Parcel ID 5-0-5) is located in the North Grafton Transit Village Overlay District(NGTVOD) (Subdistrict A). The underlying zoning district is R-40 (Residential). Pursuant toSection 13 of the Town of Grafton Zoning Bylaw, Plan Approval by the Planning Board is requiredfor proposed projects within the NGTVOD, a Chapter 40R Smart Growth District. Mixed usedevelopment is allowed as of right within Subzone A based on density requirements set forth inSection 13 of the Zoning Bylaw.The former Grafton State Hospital grounds currently include a variety of uses, including the TuftsVeterinary School campus, US Job Corps, MBTA station and other properties. The northernportion of the Site is occupied by former Grafton State Hospital buildings and forested uplands,while the southern portion consists of forested uplands, and a wetland and stream south of theinternal access road.

name: Oxford Logistics Center
notes: The Project Site consists of three undeveloped parcels (Parcel IDs: 13-B03, 13-B02, 13-B01) off of Depot Road in Oxford, MA. The Proponent also owns an adjacent 10-acre parcel in Auburn, however, there are currently  no  plans  to  develop  that  parcel.  The  10-acre  parcel  in  Auburn,  therefore,  has  not  been  considered as a part of the ‚ÄúProject Site‚Äù.   The  Project  Site is surrounded by Interstate 395 to  the  west, a railroad to  the east, a  transmission  line  right-of-way and uninhabited land to the north, and Depot Road to the south. Residential properties arelocated east of the railroad that abuts the eastern parcel boundary, however the residential propertiesare  not  anticipated to  be  impacted  by  the  proposed  Project  as  the  existing  railroad  creates  a  distinct  barrier between the Project Site and residential properties. Please refer to Figure 1 and 2 in Attachment 1 for a USGS and Aerial map of the Project Site. In the Project Site‚Äôs low-lying areas, primarily along the eastern and southern property line are several streams and culverts, including an unnamed Tributary to Wellington Brook, large areas of both federally regulated  and  unregulated  wetlands,  and  Chimney  Pond.  Chimney  Pond  is  an  impounded pond  that  appears to  have  been  dammed  in  the  1800s.  A  wetland delineation  was  completed  in  April  2021 that noted  the  dam  was  in  good  condition. However,  following  the  original  delineation,  in August  2021,  it the dam was found to be leaking through the former waterpower generation sluiceway located on the northeast side of the dam approximately 130 feet southeast of the pond spillway. The  Project  Site  contains  flood  zone  A  on  the  eastern  portion. An  electrical  right-of-way owned  by National  Grid  is  located  in  the  northern portion  of  the  property.  Mapped Natural  Heritage  and  Endangered  Species  Program habitat  is  located  within  the  boundary  of  the  National Grid easement on the northern edge  of  the  Project  Site,  however  the  limit  of  work  for  the  proposed Project will  not  fall  within  the  National  Grid  right-of-way  nor  the  endangered  species  habitat.  Please  refer  to  Figure  3  in Attachment 1 for an Environmental Constraints map.According to   the   MassGIS   2020   Environmental   Justice   Populations   mapping,   there   are   two   Environmental  Justice  Populations  within a  1-mile radius of the Project Site. Please  refer to Figure 4 in Attachment 1 for the Environmental Justice Map. They are Block Group 5, Census Tract 7531 and Block Group 3, Census Tract 7365, both in Worcester County. The Project Site borders Block Group 5, Census Tract 7531 but the Project Site is not located within an Environmental Justice Population. Block Group 5, Census  Tract  7531,  is  an  Environmental  Justice  Population  based  on  the  Minority  criteria.  The  block  group‚Äôs  median  household  income  is  $101,848,  which  is  118%  of  the  MA  median.  The  total  minority  population  within  this  block  group is  29.3%.  Block  Group  3,  Census  Tract  7365,  is  an  Environmental  Justice  Population  based  on  the  Income criteria. The Block Group‚Äôs  median  household  income  is  $48,219,  which  is  56.2%  of  the MA  median.  The  total  minority  population  in  this  Block Group  is  2.6%. Given  the  Project  Site‚Äôs  nearly immediate access  to  I-395,  separation  from  residential  properties, and the nature of the activities proposed for the site, the Proponent expects that impacts from the Project will generally be confined to the immediate Project Site and will not disproportionally adversely affect nearby EJ populations.-  4 - The Proponentcontactedthe EJ Office withinthe ExecutiveOffice of Energy and Environmental AffairsEnvironmental (EEA) Justice group which provided a list of Community-Based Organizations (CBO) in the area that may be interested in the proposed Project. These CBOs have been included on the Circulation List and the Proponent plans to conduct additional outreach to them throughout the MEPA process.

The remaining 62 units will be available to households earning between 60% and 80% of area median income. ‚Ä¢ The building is presently owned by Pine Street Inn, located at 3368 Washington Street. The existing warehouse facility on site will be demolished and uses temporarily relocated. ‚Ä¢ Pine Street is undertaking this redevelopment with TCB as its partner. After construction completion, Pine Street Inn will have a new office on-site for its case management staff and will provide intensive support services to the residents of the 140 supportive housing units. TCB will provide the ongoing physical and operational management of the property. ‚Ä¢ The design, by Boston-based RODE Architects, includes an estimated 16,000 square feet of PSI office space on the ground floor and, community space and amenities for residents. In addition, the plan offers approximately 39 parking spaces for vehicles, bike storage, and 13,400 square feet of outdoor space for residents. ‚Ä¢ The development team intends to create a separate resident services endowment to assist with providing services to residents in the long-term.

name: Verizon Communications Building
notes: Verizon Wireless intends to expand their existing telecommunications switching facility at the site. The geometry ofthe site, combined with the layout and structural design of the existing building do not allow an addition to the existingbuilding, either horizontally or vertically. The enclosed site plans depict a free standing, two-story building withassociated parking, loading, and utility connections. A multi-story structure was selected due to site constraints, beinglimited available/unoccupied space, numerous subsurface utilities, topography, and to retain vehicular circulation.The new building requires reconfiguration of the existing parking areas, driveways, and numerous subsurface utilities(together the Project). The new building has been designed to function independently of the existing building, thoughthe two will be interconnected for purposes of monitoring critical systems and functions. The proposed building hasbeen sited on an existing paved parking/storage area. While this location results in the loss of some parking andequipment storage, it does not adversely impact site circulation for the tenant, visitors, or emergency vehicles, itincreases pervious area on site, and continues to provide adequate parking for the site uses.The proposed building has a footprint of 12,572 square feet (S.F.). The ground floor and second floor are each 11,118S.F. with another 1,454 S.F. at the split-level shipping/receiving area on the north side of the building. name: 23 Cape Road Warehouse Development
notes: The proposed project is located on 21.3 acres located at 23 Cape Road (Route 140) in eastern Mendon,near both the Hopedale border to the north and the Bellingham border to the south and east. Figure 1in Attachment A shows the Project location. The Project site is identified as Parcel ID 14-114-23. It is onthe west side of Cape Road immediately north of its intersection with Whitten Street, a private roadthat extends west from Cape Road approximately 1,600 feet where it ends in a cul-de-sac. Access to thesite is will be from Whitten Street.The Project site is in Highway Business (HB) Zone in which ‚ÄòWholesale business and storage providedthere is no manufacturing or processing of materials‚Äô is a permitted use with a Special Permit for ‚ÄòAnybusiness and/or retail use permitted above by right in excess of 10,000 square feet of building area‚Äô.The stretch of Cape Road north of the Project site is a mix of commercial and some residential uses. Thesingle-runway Hopedale airport is located less than 1,000 feet north of the Project Site. The airport hasa small industrial/office park associated with it. There is a gas station on the south side of Whitten Streetat the Cape Road intersection. Beyond the gas station, the corridor is primarily residential, however,there is a large car auction facility approximately 0.6 miles to the south at the Mendon-Bellinghamborder.Structures immediately adjacent to the site include a 3-building complex comprising a car wash andauto service center, both of which front on Cape Road immediately north of Whitten Street. A gasstation and an equipment rental business front on Cape Street, immediately south of Whitten Street.The Project site is set back from Cape Road behind (i.e., west of) the businesses that front on Cape Road.The Project site consists of disturbed/cleared land on the north and south sides of Whitten Street. Thesite is scattered with piles of old asphalt, wood chips, as well as piles of rock and dirt. The Project site isshown on an aerial photo in Figure 2 in Attachment A.The topography of the site slopes east to west from an elevation of approximately 288 feet near CapeRoad down to approximately 213 feet at the western limit of the property.There are wetlands at the western edge of the site which have some associated floodplain (Zone X, 0.2%chance of annual flooding). The wetlands have been delineated and are shown on the proposed siteplan (Figure 6, Attachment A). The buffer zones are also shown on the site plan, including the local 25-foot No Disturb Zone and 50-foot No Build Zone, and the State 100-foot Buffer Zone. The site is notwithin an Area of Critical Environmental Concern (ACEC), and it does not contain any rare specieshabitat.The Project is not expected to generate greater than 150 diesel truck trips per day. Therefore, itsdesignated geographic area (DGA) is just one mile. There are no Environmental Justice (EJ) populationswithin one mile of the Project site.-4-Describe the proposed project and its programmatic and physical elements:The proposed Project consists of the construction of a 1-story, 35-foot tall, approximately 205,445square-foot warehouse building (including 5,832 sf of office space) and 226 parking spaces (206 vehicleand 20 trailer parking spaces). The building will be sited on the western portion of the site off the endof the existing cul-de-sac on Whitten Street. A driveway will ring the building to provide access to allsides of the building.Access to the Project will be from the Whitten Street right-of-way. Given the low volume of trafficexpected to be generated, no improvements are expected to be required at the intersection of WhittenStreet and Cape Road.The Project will be a net fill site, requiring approximately 92,000 cy of fill to be brought to the site. TheProject avoids the 25-foot No Disturb Zone from the BVW and requires only grading and stormwaterinfrastructure within the 100-foot Buffer zone.The Project will include a new stormwater management system, designed in accordance with MassDEPStormwater Management Standards (please refer to the Stormwater Section on page 6 for more detail).The Project will include four on-site domestic water supply wells proposed to be located east of thebuilding and parking, north of Whitten Street, and west of the car wash/auto service buildings as shownon Figure 6 in Attachment A. The new 6-inch diameter bedrock wells were constructed by MaherServices (driller) to a depth of 425 feet between May 14 and May 18, 2022. The four wells are estimatedto have a yield ranging from 5 to 20 gallons per minute (gpm) (demand is only 1.5 gpm). Three of thewells will be pumped to obtain an approval and the fourth used as a spare. Water quality tests havebeen done and are favorable. The average iron concentration is above the secondary contaminant level,but usable without treatment, and the average pH is slightly over 7, which is within the range of 6.5 to8.5 allowed by MassDEP. The wells will be connected to the building via service line below the proposedparking area and access driveway.The Project will use an on-site septic system for wastewater disposal. The septic system is proposed tobe constructed east of the proposed building and parking and south of Whitten Street with a reserveadditional septic area on the north side of Whitten Street if needed. The reserve area will be set backgreater than 100 feet from the proposed water supply well in accordance with regulations. The septicsystem will be reviewed and approved on the local level by the Mendon Board of Health.The Project will include landscaping to improve the aesthetics of what is now a degraded site and toprovide some screening from adjacent land uses.

name: Worcester CitySquare
notes: The CitySquare project area is located on the site of the former Worcester Galleria. Prior to the construction of the Galleria, this area of Downtown was composed of walkable city-blocks with active street level retail and small businesses. The vast majority of the businesses at the time were locally owned and operated and the buildings were ""human scale"" with lower heights and smaller widths with multiple buildings fronting each street block.In June of 1969, the WRA and City of Worcester celebrated the groundbreaking of the Worcester Galleria. Upon completion, this $127 million project consisted of a twenty-story office tower, eight-story office building, an enclosed galleria and mall area with 1 million square feet of retail space, and more than 4,300 enclosed parking spaces, on a thirty-four acre site. This project effectively cut off the Central Business District and Downtown from Washington Square, Shrewsbury Street, and the Canal District, creating a major impediment to future development.

notes: The proposed project has been developed in direct response to MassDevelopment‚Äôs vision for the site to stimulate economic growth for Grafton and the region beyond. Consistent with MassDevelopment‚Äôs desired concept for the site, the Proponent proposes the construction of a new approximately 200,000 square foot (sf) light industrial/flex warehousefacility with ancillary office space within two buildings (the ‚ÄúProject‚Äù). The Project will include approximately 298 parkingspaces, plus 106 banked spaces that can be constructed should the Project demand increase (in total, approximately 404spaces)4, nine of which will be Americans with Disabilities (ADA) accessible, including one accessible van space. These spaces are designed to current accessibility standards and are located such that a fully compliant accessible route can be achieved from the parking spaces to the primary building entrances. All standard parking spaces are 9 feet wide by 18 feet deep with a minimum 24-foot drive aisle. ADA compliant parking spaces are 8 feet wide with a 5-foot barrier free space and the van accessible space is also 8 feet wide with a barrier free space that is 8 feet wide. All ADA compliant spaces are 18 feet deep. The Project will also include eight electric vehicle (EV) stations, the site has been designed in a manner that will allow the Proponent to increase the number of EV spaces by up to 20% of the parking for future EV useand implementation. The proposed site layout provides ample room to easily add conduit, wire and additional charging stations, and accommodate additional transformers. There is room within the buildings‚Äô electrical rooms to add the necessary electrical subpanels, wiring, etc. that will be required to accommodate additional charging spaces when the operational need arises.The main entrance to the site will be provided by a full-access driveway located directly off Westboro Road. A second driveway will be located off of Institute Road, directly across from Audrina Lane, a subdivision roadway currently under construction as part of the approved residential project, Village at Institute Road. This driveway will be restricted to use by non-heavy vehicles, employees, and emergency vehicles only.

Directly south of the site is the Anderson Regional Transportation Center where users can commute to downtown Boston on the MBTA Commuter Rail in 25 minutes, ride the Amtrak to a variety of more distant destinations, or take the Logan Express for an express route to Logan International Airport. To the east is the I-93 onramp, providing access to one of the region‚Äôs most traveled highways. Abutting the site to the west is the location for the planned New Boston Street bridge project. MAPC‚Äôs 2018 eTOD Woburn Plan outlines this site as critical for housing and TOD. The proposed development will be harmonious with these goals by delivering transit- oriented housing to the area.Private open space is provided to the residents within an interior courtyard featuring a pool, built-in grilling stations, and other common recreational features that may include hammocks, arbors, and putting greens. On the interior, other residential common amenities would likely include a welcome/front desk area, lounge, business center, and space for a package concierge service.The Project site is between the future New Boston Street Bridge and the Anderson RTC and could prove to be an important connectivity node between the two. CC&F has planned for a future pedestrian and road connection through the Project site to connect the two.

The southern portion of the site, for which no end-user has yet been identified. is anticipated to be developed as marine industrial or ancillary use. The retail and/or restaurant uses shall be located on the ground floor of the South Building at the Highland Avenue/Gould Street intersection as shown on the Plan. Following selection of a tenant and prior to issuance of a building permit for the specific tenant improvements for the restaurant space, the tenant or the Proponent shall submit a Special Permit Amendment application to the Planning Board for a specific restaurant use as part of the Project.  Said application shall be submitted for the Board‚Äôs review and approval pursuant to By-Law Section 3.2.7.2(g) and shall include a description of the nature and operation of the restaurant use (e.g. hours of operation, number of employees, number of seats, take-out, and refuse disposal).
